main event: Multiple witnesses reported seeing an unidentified flying object near Gwinner, North Dakota on September 6, 1966. The object was described as hovering around 200 feet above the ground and approximately 40-50 feet in diameter, with a bright white pulsing light.
interesting points: One witness, Mr. Gene Gwinner, a rural mail carrier, reported seeing a bright light in the sky and pursuing it in his vehicle. He then discovered a crater-like depression in the ground measuring 18 inches in diameter and 6 inches deep, with disturbed vegetation and soil around it.
Another witness, Sergeant Elmer J. Gasser, reported seeing a cigar-shaped object with a bright white pulsing light that suddenly accelerated upward and disappeared.

A third witness, Mr. John Jones, reported seeing a circular object emitting a brilliant white light that hovered about 30 feet above the ground and then shot away rapidly. He found impressions in the ground and scorched vegetation where the object had been.
A fourth witness, Mr. Howard Gwinner, a farmer, reported observing a round, domed, silver object about 30 feet in diameter that was hovering about 5 feet above the ground for 30 minutes.
The Air Force investigated the incidents but found no physical evidence to corroborate the witness accounts.
sighted object: A bright, pulsing white light; a cigar-shaped object; a circular object; a round, domed, silver object
witnesses: Multiple, including a rural mail carrier, a sergeant, a driver, and a farmer
photographs: Yes, the report includes several photographs of the affected areas on the ground
